ergraduate and graduate levels. Epigraphy and the Greek Historian is a collection of essays that explore various ways in which inscriptions can help students reconstruct and understand Greek History.In order to engage with the study of epigraphy, this collection is divided into two parts, Athens and Athens from the outside. The contributors maintain the importance of epigraphy, arguing that, in some cases, inscriptions are the only tools we have to recover the local history of places that stand outside the main focus of ancient literary sources, which are often frustratingly Athenocentric. Ideally, the historian uses both inscriptions and literary sources to make plausible inferences and thereby weave together the disconnected threads of the past into a connected and persuasive narrative. Epigraphy and the Greek Historian is a comprehensive examination of epigraphy and a timely resource for students and scholars involved in the study of ancient history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 08. Jul 2019) 0aInscriptions, Greek. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Greece.2bisacsh1 aCooper, Craig, eeditor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015z978311066769108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311049095440uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/9781442688018423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781442688018.jpg  a978-3-11-049095-4  University of Toronto Press eBook Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  a978-3-11-066769-1  UTP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2015  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  a